      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 50-year-old obese man presents to his family physician with a recent diagnosis of nonalcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD). He is seeking advice on dietary modifications and supplements that could help prevent the progression of his liver condition. The physician reviews his diet and nutritional intake to identify any deficiencies that could be contributing to his fatty liver?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2951088",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 30334,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        1
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C)&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Dietary Choline</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Choline </strong>is essential for the <strong>synthesis of phosphatidylcholine, </strong>a key component of <strong>very-low-density lipoprotein (VLDL), </strong>which is necessary for the <strong>transport of fats out of the liver</strong>. A <strong>deficiency </strong>in <strong>choline </strong>can contribute to <strong>fat accumulation in the liver. </strong>Thus, <strong>adequate dietary </strong>intake of <strong>choline </strong>can help <strong>prevent </strong>and possibly <strong>ameliorate fatty liver</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri, sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: Thiamine</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: While thiamine is important for general metabolism, there&#39;s <strong>no direct evidence </strong>that <strong>thiamine supplementation </strong>alone would <strong>prevent fatty liver</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: Guanidinoacetate</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: This is a <strong>precursor to creatine </strong>and does <strong>not </strong>have a direct role in the <strong>prevention of fatty liver.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D: Dimethyl propionate</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: This is <strong>not </strong>a recognized <strong>treatment or preventive measure for fatty liver</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Lipotropic factors </strong>can <strong>reverse </strong>the effects of<strong> fatty liver</strong>. It includes <strong>Betaine, B12, Choline, Methionine, Inositol, Lecithin, Folic acid, Glycine, Serine.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e, p 261</span></strong></span></span></p>",
